  "content:encoded": "<p><a href=\"https://flowingdata.com/2022/10/31/election-ad-topics/\"><img width=\"750\" height=\"451\" src=\"https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-750x451.png\" class=\"attachment-medium size-medium wp-post-image\" alt=\"\" loading=\"lazy\" srcset=\"https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-750x451.png 750w, https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-1090x655.png 1090w, https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-210x126.png 210w, https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-768x462.png 768w, https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-1536x923.png 1536w, https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics.png 1986w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 750px) 100vw, 750px\" data-attachment-id=\"69545\" data-permalink=\"https://flowingdata.com/2022/10/31/election-ad-topics/election-ad-topics/\" data-orig-file=\"https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics.png\" data-orig-size=\"1986,1194\" data-comments-opened=\"0\" data-image-meta=\"{\"aperture\":\"0\",\"credit\":\"\",\"camera\":\"\",\"caption\":\"\",\"created_timestamp\":\"0\",\"copyright\":\"\",\"focal_length\":\"0\",\"iso\":\"0\",\"shutter_speed\":\"0\",\"title\":\"\",\"orientation\":\"0\"}\" data-image-title=\"election ad topics\" data-image-description=\"\" data-image-caption=\"\" data-medium-file=\"https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-750x451.png\" data-large-file=\"https://flowingdata.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/10/election-ad-topics-1090x655.png\" /></a></p><p>Midterm election day is just about here in the U.S., so the political ads are running. Harry Stevens and Colby Itkowitz, for The Washington Post, <a href=\"https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/interactive/2022/political-ads/?pwapi_token=eyJ0eXAiOiJKV1QiLCJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9..MwnjvMq5IuWPgEVIiyXkPpmQcmWZPIToecrNLvB8H90&#038;itid=gfta\">show the spending breakdown by political party and topic</a>. Bigger squares mean more spending, and more blue or more red mean more Democrat or Republican, respectively, share of the spending.</p>\n<p>The chart reminds of <a href=\"https://flowingdata.com/2012/09/07/words-used-at-the-national-conventions/\">the Shan Carter classic</a> from 2012, which visualized word usage at the National Convention. Same split and sort, but with circles.</p>\n<p><strong>Tags:</strong> <a href=\"https://flowingdata.com/tag/advertising/\" rel=\"tag\">advertising</a>, <a href=\"https://flowingdata.com/tag/election/\" rel=\"tag\">election</a>, <a href=\"https://flowingdata.com/tag/text/\" rel=\"tag\">text</a>, <a href=\"https://flowingdata.com/tag/washington-post/\" rel=\"tag\">Washington Post</a></p>",
